{"parse":{"title":"chair","pageid":4775,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|chaïr|Chair}}\n==English==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|en|chur||Bermuda}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{etymon|en|:inh|enm:chayere|tree=1}}\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*sed-}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|chayere}}, {{m|enm|chayer}}, {{m|enm|chayre}}, from {{der|en|fro|chaiere}}, {{m|fro|chaere}}, from {{der|en|la|cathedra|t=seat}}, from {{der|en|grc|καθέδρα}}, from {{m|grc|κατά|t=down}} + {{m|grc|ἕδρα|t=seat}}. Partially displaced native {{m|en|stool}} and {{m|en|settle}}, which now have more specialised senses. {{doublet|en|cathedra|chaise}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{enPR|châr}}, {{rhymes|en|ɛə(ɹ)|s=1}}\n** {{a|en|UK}}\n*** {{IPA|en|/t͡ʃɛə/|a=RP}}\n*** {{IPA|en|/t͡ʃɛː/|a=SSB}}\n*** {{IPA|en|/t͡ʃeɹ/|a=Scotland}}\n*** {{IPA|en|/t͡ʃɜː(ɹ)/|a=Lancashire,square-nurse}}\n*** {{audio|en|En-uk-chair.ogg}}\n** {{IPA|en|/t͡ʃɛɚ/|a=GA}}\n*** {{audio|en|en-us-chair.ogg}}\n** {{IPA|en|[t͡ʃeːɹ]|[t͡ʃɛːɹ]|a=CA}}\n** {{IPA|en|/t͡ʃeː/|a=AU}}\n** {{IPA|en|/t͡ʃeə/|a=NZ,non-near-square}}\n** {{IPA|en|/t͡ʃiə/|a=NZ,near-square}}\n* {{homophones|en|chare<aa:pane-pain>|cheer<aa:near-square>}}\n* {{enPR|chîr}}, {{rhymes|en|ɪə(ɹ)|s=1}}\n** {{IPA|en|/t͡ʃɪə(ɹ)/|a=dialectal or obsolete|ref1={{R:en:PEAS|4.5|119}}\n !!! {{R:en:Orton:1933|2|142|83}} !!! {{R:Stanley SET|I|6|16}}}}\n\n===Noun===\n[[Image:Chair.png|thumb|right|A chair (item of furniture).]]\n[[Image:Schienenstühle, Laschenstoß.jpg|thumb|right|Chairs (rail supports on a railway).]]\n{{wp|[[+|+ (furniture)]]}}\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|furniture for sitting}} An item of [[furniture]] used to sit on or in, comprising a [[seat]], legs or wheels, back, and sometimes arm rests, for use by one person.\n#: {{ux|en|All I need to weather a snowstorm is hot coffee, a warm fire, a good book and a comfortable '''chair'''.}}\n#: {{ux|en|I sat on my '''chair''' to have dinner.}}\n#* {{RQ:Maxwell Mirror and the Lamp|chapter=12|passage=There were many wooden '''chairs''' for the bulk of his visitors, and two wicker arm'''chairs''' with red cloth cushions for superior people. From the packing-cases had emerged some Indian clubs,{{nb...}}, and all these articles{{nb...}} made a scattered and untidy decoration that Mrs. Clough assiduously dusted and greatly cherished.}}\n#* {{RQ:Allingham China Governess|chapter=19|passage=Meanwhile Nanny Broome was recovering from her initial panic and seemed anxious to make up for any kudos she might have lost, by exerting her personality to the utmost. She took the policeman's helmet and placed it on a '''chair''', and unfolded his tunic to shake it and fold it up again for him.}}\n# {{senseid|en|chairperson}}{{lb|en|often with definite article, also written ''[[Chair]]''}} {{clipping of|en|chairperson}}.\n#: {{ux|en|Under the rules of order adopted by the board, the '''chair''' may neither make nor second motions.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|date=March 23, 1658-9|author=[[w:Thomas Burton (politician)|Thomas Burton]]|editor=w:John Towill Rutt|title=Diary|location=London|publisher=w:Henry Colburn|year_published=1828|page=243|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=eVxjAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA243&lpg=PA243\n|passage=The '''Chair''' behaves himself like a Busby amongst so many school-boys{{...}}and takes a little too much on him.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=September 5, 1887|work=The Times\n|passage=It can hardly be conceived that the '''Chair''' would fail to gain the support of the House.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1950|month=March|author=Michael Robbins|title=Dr. Lardner's \"Railway Economy\"|journal=Railway Magazine|page=153|text=He was elected to the '''chair''' of Natural Philosophy and Astronomy in 1827 at the newly-founded London University, and became prominent in railway controversies in the 'thirties, when he came off second best in a dispute with Daniel Gooch about the effects of speed on the human frame.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2020 June 3|author=Lilian Greenwood talks to Paul Stephen|title=Rail's 'underlying challenges' remain|journal=Rail|page=34|text=She adds: \"I'd also like to think that as '''chair''' I was friendly but firm. I wanted to encourage people to give evidence, while there are others who need to be coaxed, held to account and asked tough questions.\"}}\n# {{lb|en|usually with definite article}} The post or position of chairperson.\n#: {{ux|en|The meeting began, with Mr Roberts in the '''chair'''.}}\n# {{senseid|en|orchestra position}} {{lb|en|music}} The seating position of a particular musician in an orchestra.\n#: {{ux|en|My violin teacher used to play first '''chair''' with the Boston Pops.}}\n# {{senseid|en|rail-to-sleeper hardware}} {{lb|en|rail transport}} A [[cast-iron]] [[component]] used on [[railway]]s to support [[bullhead rail]]s and secure them to the [[sleeper]]s.\n#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1934|month=February|title=The Why and The Wherefore: Chair-keys|journal=Railway Magazine|page=139|text=The wooden or steel keys used to secure bull-head rails in their '''chairs''' are usually driven in the direction of the traffic, so that the effects of rail-creep may be made use of to wedge the keys more firmly, rather than to encourage them to drop out.}}\n# {{senseid|en|conformer of cyclohexane}} {{lb|en|organic compound|physical chemistry}} One of two possible [[conformer]]s of [[cyclohexane]] rings (the other being [[boat]]), shaped roughly like a chair.\n# {{senseid|en|electric chair}} {{lb|en|informal|with ''the''}} {{ellipsis of|en|electric chair|t=device used for performing execution}}.\n#: {{ux|en|The court will show no mercy; if he gets convicted, it's the '''chair''' for him.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=June 1920|journal=w:The Electrical Experimenter|location=New York|page=216|column=2|passage=\"It was me. And I'm glad, damned glad, I didn't croak him. With this slick guy after me, it would be me for the '''chair'''.\"}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:Agatha Christie|title=Murder on the Orient Express|location=London|publisher=HarperCollins|year=1934|year_published= 2017|chapter=8|page=251|passage='All for a pig of a man who should have gone to the '''chair'''.'}}\n#* {{quote-av|en|year=1949|writer=w:Isobel Lennart|title=w:Holiday Affair|role=Carl Davis|actor=Wendell Corey|passage=Believe it or not, it only looked like I was trying to send you to the '''chair'''.}}\n#* {{quote-av|en|director=w:Ivan Reitman|title=w:Ghostbusters II|date=16 June 1989|text=\"Scoleri Brothers!\"  \"Friends of yours?\"  \"I tried them for murder!  Gave them the '''chair'''!\"}}\n#* {{quote-web|en|date=2014-04-18|author=John McBain, as quoted|work=w:Sky News|title=Judge Lashes Out At Convicted Murderer|url=https://news.sky.com/story/judge-lashes-out-at-convicted-murderer-10409067|text=I hope you die in prison as well — and if this was a death penalty state you'd be getting the '''chair'''.}}\n# {{senseid|en|distinguished professorship}} {{lb|en|education}} A [[distinguished]] [[professorship]] at a university.\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Michael Inwood|title=Martin Heidegger: the philosopher who fell for Hitler &#91;print version: Hitler's philosopher&#93;|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/10739165/Martin-Heidegger-the-philosopher-who-fell-for-Hitler.html|work={{w|The Daily Telegraph}} (Review)|location=London|date=12 April 2014|page=R11|passage=In 1928 [[w:Martin Heidegger|&#91;Martin&#93; Heidegger]] succeeded [[w:Edmund Husserl|&#91;Edmund&#93; Husserl]] to take a '''chair''' at Freiburg {{...}}}}\n# {{senseid|en|gig as conveyance}} A [[vehicle]] for one person; either a [[sedan]] borne upon poles, or a two-wheeled carriage drawn by one horse; a [[gig]].\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 6-2|II|v|104|2|Enter Mortimer, brought in a '''Chayre''', and Iaylors.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1777|author=w:Richard Brinsley Sheridan|title=The School for Scandal|section=IV.iii\n|passage=She always leaves her '''Chair''' at the milliner's in the next Street.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1712|author=w:Alexander Pope|chapter=w:The Rape of the Lock|title=The Beauties of Pope|location=London|publisher=G. Kearsley|year_published=1783|page=32|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=cywhAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA26&lpg=PA32|passage=Think what an equipage thou haſt in air, <br> And view with ſcorn two pages and a '''chair'''.}}\n#* {{RQ:Landon Ethel Churchill|page=211|volume=II|passage=The '''chairs''' came at the appointed hour, and Ethel could not but be amused at the glimpses she had of the park along which they were carried; although haunted by misgivings as to the judiciousness of their destination. They were set down in a hall of large dimensions, hung round with portraits, and filled with servants, who had more the air of guards.}}\n# {{senseid|en|office of authority such as bishopry}} The seat or office of a person in [[authority]], such as a [[judge]] or [[bishop]].\n# An assigned position in a [[beauty salon]] or [[barbershop]].\n#: {{ux|en|Melinda has the best '''chair''' in the salon.}}\n# {{lb|en|glassblowing}} {{rfdef|en}} <!-- team of glassblower + assistants? -->\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|Adirondack chair\n|almost fall off one's chair\n|arm-chair\n|armchair\n|banana chair\n|barber chair\n|barber-chair\n|Barcelona chair\n|bar chair|chair car\n|basket chair\n|bath chair,Bath chair\n|beach chair\n|bedchair\n|birth chair\n|birthing chair|\n|boatswain's chair\n|booster chair\n|bosun's chair\n|bowl chair\n|butterfly chair\n|camping chair\n|cantilever chair\n|Cape Cod chair\n|chairback\n|chair bed\n|chairborne\n|chairbound\n|chair conformation\n|chaircover\n|chair days\n|chairdrobe\n|chairfast\n|chairfolk\n|chair force\n|chairful\n|chairholder\n|chairhood\n|chairlady\n|chairless\n|chair-lift\n|chair lift\n|chairlift\n|chairlike\n|chairmaker\n|chairmaking\n|chairman\n|chair mat\n|chairness\n|chairobics\n|chair of state\n|chairoplane\n|chair organ\n|chairperson\n|chair plug\n|chair rail\n|chair seat\n|chair seater\n|chairship\n|chairside\n|chair time\n|chair umpire\n|chair up\n|chairward\n|chairwarmer\n|chairwise\n|chairwoman\n|chairwork\n|close chair\n|club chair\n|cochair\n|co-chair\n|confessional chair\n|cricket chair\n|Cromwellian chair\n|cuck chair\n|deck-chair\n|deck chair\n|desk chair\n|dining chair\n|Eames chair\n|ear chair\n|easy chair\n|easy-chair\n|elbow chair\n|elbow-chair\n|electric chair\n|Elijah chair\n|empty chair\n|endowed chair\n|fall off one's chair\n|farthingale chair\n|feeding chair\n|fighting chair\n|fireman's chair knot\n|first chair\n|flag chair\n|folding chair\n|fountain chair\n|French chair\n|Gainsborough chair\n|game chair\n|gaming chair\n|geriatric chair\n|geri chair\n|gestatorial chair\n|give someone the chair\n|Glastonbury chair\n|grandfather chair\n|grandfather's chair\n|guest chair\n|half-chair\n|headchair\n|highchair\n|high chair\n|hot chair\n|hoverchair\n|ice cream chair\n|ice-cream chair\n|invalid chair\n|Judas chair\n|kneeling chair\n|lady's chair\n|Laurentian chair\n|lawn chair\n|lounge chair\n|Martha Washington chair\n|massage chair\n|Mendlesham chair\n|mercy chair\n|Merlin chair\n|monk chair\n|monk's chair\n|Morris chair\n|musical chairs\n|Muskoka chair\n|nearly fall off one's chair\n|night chair\n|nursing chair\n|office chair\n|papasan chair\n|patio chair\n|peacock chair\n|planter's chair\n|pool chair\n|potty chair\n|powerchair\n|pull up a chair\n|pushchair\n|reception chair\n|revolving chair\n|rocking chair\n|rocking-chair\n|rocking chair money\n|rocking-chair money\n|rolling chair\n|Roman chair\n|Roorkee chair\n|rotating chair\n|rout chair\n|Savonarola chair\n|sedan chair\n|semi-easy chair\n|shower chair\n|side chair\n|sledge chair\n|slipper chair\n|smoker's chair\n|socialism of the chair\n|socialist of the chair\n|soda fountain chair\n|spectator chair\n|stairchair\n|steamer chair\n|step chair\n|stepchair\n|sunchair\n|swivel chair\n|swivel-chair\n|take a chair\n|take the chair\n|tiger chair\n|tramp chair\n|tub chair\n|vice-chair\n|vice chair\n|walking chair\n|wheelchair\n|Windsor chair\n|wingback chair\n|wing chair\n|X-chair\n}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{sense|furniture}} {{l|en|stool}}, {{l|en|couch}}, {{l|en|sofa}}, {{l|en|settee}}, {{l|en|love seat}}, {{l|en|bench}}.\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|as|চেয়াৰ|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|bn|চেয়ার|bor=1|alts=1}}\n* {{desc|bor=1|or|ଚେଆର୍|ଚିୟାର୍|ଚିଆର}}\n* {{desc|syl|ꠌꠤꠀꠞ|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|tpi|sea}}, {{l|tpi|sia}}\n* {{desc|to|sea|bor=1}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|furniture}}{{multitrans|data=\n* Afrikaans: {{tt+|af|stoel}}\n* Ahom: {{tt|aho|𑜄𑜂𑜫}}\n* Albanian: {{tt+|sq|karrige|f}}\n* Altai:\n*: Southern Altai: {{t|alt|отургыш}}\n* Amharic: {{tt|am|ወንበር}}\n* Arabic: {{tt+|ar|كُرْسِيّ|m}}, {{tt+|ar|مَقْعَد|m}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{tt|arz|كرسي|m|tr=korsī}}\n*: Iraqi Arabic: {{tt|acm|سكملي|m|tr=skamlī}}\n*: Moroccan Arabic: {{tt|ary|كرسي|m|tr=kursi}}, {{tt|ary|شلية|tr=šalya}}\n*: South Levantine Arabic: {{tt|ajp|كرسي|m|tr=kersí}}\n* Aramaic:\n*: Classical Syriac: {{tt|syc|ܟܘܪܣܝܐ|m|tr=kursəyā}}\n*: Hebrew script: {{tt|arc|כורסיא|m|tr=kursəyā}}\n* Armenian: {{tt+|hy|աթոռ}}\n* Aromanian: {{tt+|rup|scamnu}}\n* Assamese: {{tt|as|চকী}}\n* Asturian: {{tt+|ast|siella|f}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{tt+|az|stul}}, {{tt+|az|oturacaq}}, {{tt+|az|kürsü}}\n* Bashkir: {{tt|ba|ултырғыс}}\n* Basque: {{tt|eu|katedra}}, {{tt+|eu|aulki}}\n* Belarusian: {{tt|be|крэ́сла|n}}, {{tt|be|сто́лец|m}}, {{tt|be|стул|m}}\n* Bengali: {{tt+|bn|চেয়ার}}, {{tt+|bn|আসন}}, {{tt+|bn|কেদারা}}, {{tt+|bn|কুরসি}}\n* Bikol:\n*: Central Bikol: {{tt+|bcl|tukawan}}\n* Bislama: {{tt|bi|jea}}\n* Breton: {{tt+|br|kador|f}}\n* Bulgarian: {{tt+|bg|стол|m}}\n* Burmese: {{tt+|my|ထိုင်ခုံ}}, {{tt+|my|ကုလားထိုင်}}\n* Buryat: {{tt|bua|һандали}}, {{tt|bua|стул}}\n* Carpathian Rusyn: {{tt|rue|столе́ць|m}}\n* Catalan: {{tt+|ca|cadira|f}}\n* Cebuano: {{tt|ceb|siya}}, {{tt|ceb|linkoranan}}\n* Chechen: {{tt|ce|гӏант}}\n* Cherokee: {{tt|chr|ᎦᏍᎩᎶ}}\n* Cheyenne: {{tt|chy|táxe'ėséestȯtse}}\n* Chichewa: {{tt|ny|mpando}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Cantonese: {{tt|yue|凳//櫈|tr=dang3}}, {{tt+|yue|椅子|tr=ji2 zi2}}\n*: Dungan: {{tt|dng|йизы}}\n*: Eastern Min: {{tt|cdo|椅囝|tr=iē-giāng}}\n*: Hakka: {{tt|hak|凳仔|tr=ten-é}} {{qualifier|Sixian, PFS}}, {{tt|hak|椅仔}} {{qualifier|Meixian, Guangdong}}\n*: Hokkien: {{tt+|nan-hbl|椅仔|tr=í-á}}\n*: Mandarin: {{tt+|cmn|椅子|tr=yǐzi}}, {{tt+|cmn|凳子}} {{qual|colloquial}}\n*: Northern Min: {{tt|mnp|椅仔|tr=ǐ-ciě}}\n*: Wu: {{tt|wuu|椅子}}\n*: Xiang: {{tt|hsn|椅子|tr=i3 zr}}\n* Circassian:\n*: West Circassian: {{tt|ady|пхъэнтӏэкӏу}}, {{qualifier|Shapsug}} {{tt|ady|пхъэтӏэкӏу}}, {{tt|ady|онэгу}}\n* Coptic: {{tt|cop|ⲧⲟⲧⲥ|m}}\n* Cornish: {{tt|kw|kador|f}}\n* Crimean Tatar: {{tt|crh|stul}}\n* Czech: {{tt+|cs|židle|f}}\n* Dalmatian: {{tt|dlm|catraida|f}}\n* Danish: {{tt+|da|stol|c}}\n* Dhivehi: {{tt+|dv|ގޮނޑި}}\n* Dutch: {{tt+|nl|stoel|m}}, {{tt+|nl|zetel|m}}\n* Esperanto: {{tt+|eo|seĝo}}\n* Estonian: {{tt+|et|tool}}\n* Faroese: {{tt|fo|stólur|m}}\n* Fijian: {{tt+|fj|idabedabe}}\n* Finnish: {{tt+|fi|tuoli}}\n* French: {{tt+|fr|chaise|f}}, {{tt+|fr|fauteuil|m}}\n* Frisian:\n*: North Frisian:\n*:: Föhr-Amrum: {{tt|frr|stuul|m}}\n*:: Heligoland: {{tt|frr|Stuul|m}}\n*:: Mooring: {{tt|frr|stölj|m}}\n*: Old Frisian: {{tt|ofs|stōl|m}}\n*: Saterland Frisian: {{tt|stq|Stoul|m}}\n* Friulian: {{tt|fur|cjadree|f}}, {{tt|fur|čhadree|f}}\n* Galician: {{tt+|gl|cadeira|f}}\n* Georgian: {{tt+|ka|სკამი}}\n* German: {{tt+|de|Sessel|m}}, {{tt+|de|Stuhl|m}}\n* Gothic: {{t|got|𐍃𐍄𐍉𐌻𐍃|m}}\n* Greek: {{tt+|el|καρέκλα|f}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{tt|grc|δίφρος|m}}, {{tt|grc|ἕδρα|f}}, {{q|Epic}} {{tt|grc|θᾶκος|m}}\n* Greenlandic: {{tt|kl|issiavik}}\n* Guarani:\n*: Paraguayan Guarani: {{tt-check|gug|apyka'i}}\n* Gujarati: {{tt|gu|ખુરસી|f}}, {{tt|gu|આસંદી|f}}\n* Haitian Creole: {{tt|ht|chèz}}\n* Hawaiian: {{tt|haw|noho}}\n* Hebrew: {{tt+|he|כיסא|m|tr=kisé|alt=כיסא \\ כִּסֵּא}}\n* Hiligaynon: {{tt|hil|lingkoranan}}\n* Hindi: {{tt+|hi|आसंद|m}}, {{tt+|hi|कुरसी|f}}\n* Hmong:\n*: White Hmong: {{t|mww|rooj}}\n* Hungarian: {{tt+|hu|szék}}\n* Iban: {{tt|iba|kerusi}}\n* Icelandic: {{tt+|is|stóll}}\n* Ido: {{tt+|io|stulo}}\n* Indonesian: {{tt+|id|kursi}}\n* Interlingua: {{tt|ia|sede}}, {{tt|ia|sedia}}\n* Irish: {{tt+|ga|cathaoir|f}}\n* Isan: {{tt|tts|เก้าอี้|tr=kêāxī̂}}\n* Italian: {{tt+|it|sedia|f}}, {{tt+|it|seggiola|f}}\n* Japanese: {{tt+|ja|椅子|tr=いす, isu}}, {{tt+|ja|ソファ|tr=sofa}} {{q|as part of a sofa set}}\n* Kabuverdianu: {{tt|kea|kadera}}\n* Kalmyk: {{tt|xal|сандл}}\n* Kamba: {{tt|kam|kibila}}\n* Kannada: {{tt+|kn|ಕುರ್ಚಿ}}\n* Kapampangan: {{tt|pam|luklukan}}, {{tt|pam|tabureti}}\n* Kashubian: {{tt|csb|stółk|m}}\n* Kazakh: {{tt+|kk|орындық}}\n* Khmer: {{tt+|km|កៅអី}}\n* Kikuyu: {{tt|ki|gete}}\n* Kimaragang: {{tt|kqr|bangku}}\n* Kongo: {{t|kg|kiti}}\n* Korean: {{tt+|ko|의자(椅子)}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Central Kurdish: {{tt|ckb|کورسی}}\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{tt+|kmr|kursî|f}}, {{tt+|kmr|sendelî}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{tt|ky|орундук}}\n* Lao: {{tt+|lo|ຕັ່ງ}}, {{tt|lo|ເກົ້າອີ້}}\n* Latgalian: {{tt|ltg|krāslys}}\n* Latin: {{tt|la|sella|f}}, {{tt+|la|sēdēs|f}}, {{tt|la|sedīle|n}}, {{tt|la|cathedra|f}}, {{tt|la|solium|n}}\n* Latvian: {{tt+|lv|krēsls|m}}\n* Ligurian: {{tt|lij|carêga|f}}\n* Limburgish: {{tt+|li|stool|m}}\n* Lingala: {{t|ln|kiti}}\n* Lithuanian: {{tt+|lt|kėdė|f}}\n* Lombard: {{tt+|lmo|scagn}}, {{tt+|lmo|cadrega}}\n* Louisiana Creole: {{tt|lou|lashèz}}, {{tt|lou|lashèj}}, {{tt|lou|shèj}}, {{tt|lou|shèz}}\n* Lü: {{tt|khb|ᦎᧂᧈ}}\n* Luhya: {{tt|luy|endebe}}\n* Luxembourgish: {{tt+|lb|Stull|m}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|стол|m}}, {{tt|mk|столица|f}}\n* Maguindanao: {{tt|mdh|kursi}}\n* Malay: {{tt+|ms|kerusi}}\n*: Brunei Malay: {{tt|kxd|kerusi}}\n* Malayalam: {{tt+|ml|കസേര}}\n* Maltese: {{tt+|mt|siġġu|m}}\n* Manchu: {{tt|mnc|ᠨᡳᡴᡝᡴᡠ ᠮᡠᠯᠠᠨ}}, {{tt|mnc|ᡳᠰᡝ}}\n* Mandingo:\n*: Mandinka: {{tt|mnk|sirango}}\n* Manx: {{tt|gv|caair}}\n* Māori: {{tt+|mi|tūru}}, {{tt|mi|nohoanga}}\n* Maranao: {{tt|mrw|korsi'}}\n* Marathi: {{tt+|mr|खुर्ची|f}}\n* Melanau:\n*: Central Melanau: {{tt|mel|keresik}}\n* Mongolian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{tt+|mn|сандал}}, {{tt+|mn|суудал}}\n*: Mongolian script: {{tt